Synopsis
========

  emxdoc -t [-fr] [-o <output>] <input>
  emxdoc -i [-acfgr] [-n <start>] [-o <output>] [-x <xref>] <input>
  emxdoc -k [-o <output>] <input>...
  emxdoc -l [-fr] [-o <output>] <input>
  emxdoc -m [-o <output>] <input>...


Commands:

-t      Create .doc file (plain text)

-i      Create .ipf file (for IPFC)

-k      Create .ndx file (for EPM)

-l      Create .tex file (for LaTeX) -- not yet implemented

-m      Merge directory files into cross reference file


Options:

-a      Use concatenating instead of calling .inf files.  Without -a,
        a reference to a label in another .inf file causes that .inf
        file to be called, that is, a new VIEW instance is created.
        With -a, .inf files are assumed to be concatenated.  Use -n
        with -a

-b <number>

        Select line breaking algorithm for -t.  Possible values are 0
        (default) and 1 (slow):
        0       greedy algorithm, filling lines as much as possible
        1       minimize sum of (target_width - actual_width)^2

-c      Use color (light blue) instead of slanted font for
        highlighting with þpa, þsl, þem, þformat slanted and
        `þformat emphasize'

-e <character>

        Set the escape character.  By default, emxdoc uses þ as the
        escape character.  This documentation always uses þ as the
        escape character.  You can choose a different escape character
        with the -e option.  The character code is given in decimal,
        octal, or hexadecimal, using C notation.  If the argument of
        the -e option is a single non-digit character, that character
        is used as the escape character

-f      Enable French spacing.  With -f, one space is used after the
        end of a sentence, without -f, two spaces are used

-g      Gather global directory data

-h <file>
        Use hyphenation table (for -t -b1)

-n <start>
        Define first ID number, for use with -a.  The default is 1

-o <output>
        Set name of output file (default: stdout)

-r      Make output file read-only

-w <level>
        Set the warning level:
        0       No warnings (default)
        1       Text starting in first column
        2       Text should be inserted here

-x <xref>
        Use cross reference file, created by -m command


Creating a .doc file
====================

  emxdoc -t -o sample.doc sample.src


Creating an .inf file
=====================

  emxdoc -i -o sample.ipf sample.src
  ipfc sample.ipf /inf


Creating loosely related .inf files
===================================

  emxdoc -ig -o sample1.dir sample1.src
  emxdoc -ig -o sample2.dir sample2.src
  emxdoc -m -o sample.dir sample1.dir sample2.dir
  emxdoc -i -o sample1.ipf -x sample.dir sample1.src
  emxdoc -i -o sample2.ipf -x sample.dir sample1.src
  ipfc sample1.ipf /inf
  ipfc sample2.ipf /inf


Creating .inf files to be concatenated
======================================

  emxdoc -ig -n1 -o sample1.dir sample1.src
  emxdoc -ig -n1000 -o sample2.dir sample2.src
  emxdoc -m -o sample.dir sample1.dir sample2.dir
  emxdoc -i -n1 -o sample1.ipf -x sample.dir sample1.src
  emxdoc -i -n1000 -o sample2.ipf -x sample.dir sample1.src
  ipfc sample1.ipf /inf
  ipfc sample2.ipf /inf

Note that you'll get

  151: No res for this reference [...]

warning messages from ipfc.  Use -n to avoid overlapping ranges of
IDs.


Tags
====

Tags start by default with þ (code 254).  You can use the -e option to
choose a different character. There are two types of tags:

- tags which start in the first column

- tags used in text


[...TODO...]


Words
-----

To find a word, emxdoc skips ( * and ` characters, and then takes all
characters until one of the characters , ; ! ? ' is found.  The
characters . and : terminates a word if followed by a blank or by the
end of the line.  The character ) terminates a word if properly
nested.  The character [ terminates a word inside þprototype.  After a
word, terminating characters are skipped.  Example: The input

    If the -s[<blah>] option or example.dll (in LIBPATH) are missing,
    example() fails.

consists of the following words:

    If
    the
    -s[<bla>]
    option
    or
    example.dll
    in
    LIBPATH
    are
    missing
    example()
    fails


Tags which start in the first column
------------------------------------

þif <condition>
þelse
þendif

   Conditionally include or exclude sections of the input file.  þif
   statements may be nested to up to 8 levels.

   The <condition> consists of the operators &, | and !, the operands
   ipf, text and latex (which are true if -i, -t or -l, respectively,
   is in effect), false, true, variables (see þset) and parentheses.

   Example:

        þif text
        þh1 Table of Contents
        þtoc
        þendif

þset <name> <value>

   Set the variable <name> to <value>.  Variable names must be start
   with a letter.  The remaining characters may be letters, digits or
   `_'.  Letter case is significant.  Possible values are `false' and
   `true'.  Variables can be used for þif.

þformat <style> <word>...

   Define <word>s to be formatted in style <style>.  Possible choices
   for <style> are:

        abbrev          Abbreviation (must end with .)
        bold            Boldface
        emphasize       Emphasized (slanted, uppercase for -t)
        param           Parameter (slanted lower case for -i)
        slanted         Slanted (or colored if -c is used)
        syntax          <...> slanted, [|] bold, rest tty
        tty             Fixed-width typewriter font
        underline       Underlined

    Example:

        þformat syntax <style> <word>
        þformat tty .exe .com
        þformat abbrev etc.

   abbrev is orthogonal to the other styles.  It means that the period
   at the end of the word doesn't end a sentence (see the -f option).

þreplace <word> <replacement>

   Replace <word> with <replacement>, which is emxdoc input.  Example:

        þreplace <table> þtt{<}þsl{table}þtt{>}

   þreplace takes precedence over formatting styles.  <replacement>
   should not directly or indirectly contain <word>.

þspecial <mode> <word> <replacement>

   Replace <word> with <replacement> on output in mode <mode> (text,
   ipf or latex).

     Example:

        þspecial latex TeX \TeX{}

þh<level>[<flags>] <heading>
þh- <heading>
þh= <heading>

   Start new section of level <level> (1 through 3).  <heading> is the
   section heading.  Example:

        þh1 Getting started

   If <flags> includes `u', the section is unnumbered and does not
   appear in the table of contents of the output file when creating a
   text file.

   If <flags> includes `h' (hide), the section will not appear in the
   Contents window.

   þh- and þh= create an underlined section heading which does not appear
   in the table of contents and does not start a new panel.


þtoc

   Insert table of contents.  Example:

        þiftext
        þh1 Table of Contents
        þtoc
        þendif


þipfminitoc

   In -i mode, insert a table of hypertext links to the subsections of
   the current section.

þtitle <title>

   Define title of .inf document.  Example:

        þtitle Formatting documents with emxdoc


þlabel <label>

   Define the label <label> to refer to the current section.  The
   label can be used with þhpt{} and þref{}.  Example:

        þlabel defining label


þlanguage <language>

   Define the language to be used for emxdoc-generated text.  Valid
   languages are `english' (which is the default) and `german'.


þsyntax <style>

   Select the syntax style recognized by þsy{}.  Possible values for
   <style> are `emx' (which is the default) and `dvidrv'.

þindex <term>

   Put <term> into the top level of the index.  Example:

        þindex top level


þi1 <term>

   Put <term> into the top level of the index (unless already done)
   and make this the first level entry for þi2.  If <term> is not
   present, disable þi2.


þi2 <term>

   Put <term> into the second level of the index, under the term most
   recently used with þi1.  Example:

        þi1 indexing
        þi2 levels


þkeyword <keyword>...

    Define keyword for EPM.  You can give multiple keywords, separated
    by spaces.


þipf
þendipf

    Insert lines of IPF commands between þipf and þendipf as-is into
    the output file if -i is used.  Ignore lines if -t is used


þtext
þendtext

    Insert lines between þtext and þendtext as-is into the output file
    if -t is used.  Ignore lines if -i is used


þdescription
þitem <term>
  <description>
þenddescription

    Describe terms.  Each description is started with þitem.  The term
    to be described is given on the same line as þitem.  Paragraphs
    between þdescription and þenddescription are indended.  If <term>
    is short enough, its description starts on the same line.
    Otherwise, it starts on the next line.


þlist
þitem <term>
  <description>
þendlist

    Like þdescription, but the description is always put on a new
    line.

þenumerate
þitem
  <paragraph>
þendenumeate

    Numbered list of items.  þitem starts a new item.  Each item is
    preceded by a number.  The paragraphs between þitemize and
    þenditemize are indended.

þitemize
þitem
  <paragraph>
þenditemize

    Unordered list of items.  þitem starts a new item.  Each item is
    preceded by a mark.  The paragraphs between þitemize and
    þenditemize are indended.

þverbatim
þendverbatim

    Output lines between þverbatim and þendverbatim as-is, maintaining
    line breaks and leading spaces.  A fixed-width typewriter font is
    used.  The current indentation is used.


þexample
þendexample

    Like þverbatim, but indent by 4 characters.


þindent
þendindent

    Use an additional indentation of 4 characters for paragraphs
    between þindent and þendindent.


þtypewriter
þendtypewriter

    Like þident, but use þtt{} as default.  Note that line breaks and
    leading spaces are not maintained in the output.


þtable [indent] <width>...
  <column1> ³ <column2>...
  ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÅÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
  <column1> ³ <column2>...
  <column1> ³ <column2>...
þendtable

    Unfortunately, IPFC doesn't like font changes in tables.


þfunction <name>...

    Used in a library reference.  With -i, þfunction starts a new
    panel.  With -t, þfunction inserts a dashed line.  All function
    and variable names described in this section should be listed in
    the þfunction line, separated by spaces.  If a <name> does contain
    (), it is automatically added to the list of words to be formatted
    specially, using tty style.  The section heading is constructed by
    listing the names, separated by commas.  The last two names are
    separated by ` and '.  A level-two index entry is created for each
    <name>.  Therefore, an þi1 tag must have been used before
    þfunction.  With -k, þfunction defines a keyword.


þcompat <name>...

    Defines the compatibility of the function.  This tag, if used,
    must precede þheaders if present.  If þheaders is not present, it
    must precede þprototype.  With -t, the compatibility is shown at
    the right end of the first line created by þheaders.  If þheaders
    is not used, a line is inserted by þprototype.  The names are
    inclosed in square brackets.  With -i, þendprototype inserts the
    `Compatibility:' section, using the names defined with þcompat.
    The names are separated by spaces.


þheaders
þendheaders

    List include files.


þparam <name>...

    Format the names using þpa{}.  This definition is local to the
    current function or variable description, which ends at the next
    þfunction or þh1 tag.


þprototype
þendprototype

    Function prototype in library reference manual.


þreturnvalue

    Starts a new section, titled `Return value:'.


þrestrictions

    Starts a new section, titled `Restrictions:'.


þimplementation

    Starts a new section, titled `Implementation-defined behavior:'.


þbugs

    Starts a new section, titled `Bugs:'.


þerrors

    Starts a new section, titled `Errors:'.


þhints

    Starts a new section, titled `Hints:'.


þseealso

    Cross references in library reference manual.


þsamplefile

    Pointer to sample file in library reference manual.


þsamplecode
þendsamplecode

    Sample code in library reference manual.



Tags used in text
-----------------

þ.

    Insert a period which marks the end of a sentence.  Required after
    abbreviations.

þbreak

    Force line break

þtt{<text>}

    Use fixed-width typewriter font for <text>

þsl{<text>}

    Use slanted font for <text>.  Use color instead if -c option is in
    effect

þbf{<text>}

    Use bold font for <text>

þem{<text>}

    Emphasize <text>.  This is done by using a slanted font for -i,
    using italics for -l and upcasing for -t

þsy{<text>}

    Format <text> as grammer: þbf{} is used for the three characters [
    | ], þsl{} is used for terms enclosed in angle brackets
    (<whatever> -- the angle brackets are removed if -i is used) and
    for * and # (and + for þsyntax dvidrv) at the end of <text>, þtt{}
    is used for everything else

þpa{<text>}

    Use þsl{} and convert to lower-case if the -i option is used.
    Unmodified if -t is used

þul{<text>}

    Underline

þhpt{<label>}

    Hypertext-reference to <label>, which is inserted into the output
    file

þref{<label>}

   Insert section number of <label>

